Note:
Runa Standard Library: Linear Regression

Implementation of linear regression algorithms including ordinary least squares,
ridge regression, and polynomial regression with gradient descent optimization.
:End Note

Import "../../algorithms" as Algorithms
Import "../../math/core" as Math
Import "../../../../collections" as Collections

Note: Linear Regression Model
Type called "LinearRegression":
    coefficients as Algorithms.Vector
    intercept as Float
    fit_intercept as Boolean
    normalize as Boolean
    regularization as String
    alpha as Float
    fitted as Boolean
    n_features as Integer

Process called "create_linear_regression" that takes fit_intercept as Boolean returns LinearRegression:
    Return LinearRegression with:
        coefficients as Algorithms.Vector with size as 0 and data as list
        intercept as 0.0
        fit_intercept as fit_intercept
        normalize as false
        regularization as "none"
        alpha as 1.0
        fitted as false
        n_features as 0

Process called "create_ridge_regression" that takes alpha as Float returns LinearRegression:
    Return LinearRegression with:
        coefficients as Algorithms.Vector with size as 0 and data as list
        intercept as 0.0
        fit_intercept as true
        normalize as false
        regularization as "l2"
        alpha as alpha
        fitted as false
        n_features as 0

Process called "create_lasso_regression" that takes alpha as Float returns LinearRegression:
    Return LinearRegression with:
        coefficients as Algorithms.Vector with size as 0 and data as list
        intercept as 0.0
        fit_intercept as true
        normalize as false
        regularization as "l1"
        alpha as alpha
        fitted as false
        n_features as 0

Note: Fitting methods
Process called "fit_linear_regression" that takes model as LinearRegression and X as Algorithms.Matrix and y as Algorithms.Vector returns LinearRegression:
    Set model.n_features to X.cols
    
    Note: Add intercept column if needed
    Let X_processed be X
    If model.fit_intercept:
        Set X_processed to add_intercept_column with matrix as X
    
    Note: Normalize features if specified
    If model.normalize:
        Set X_processed to normalize_features with matrix as X_processed
    
    Match model.regularization:
        When "none":
            fit_ols with model as model and X as X_processed and y as y
        When "l2":
            fit_ridge with model as model and X as X_processed and y as y
        When "l1":
            fit_lasso with model as model and X as X_processed and y as y
        Otherwise:
            fit_ols with model as model and X as X_processed and y as y
    
    Set model.fitted to true
    Return model

Note: Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)
Process called "fit_ols" that takes model as LinearRegression and X as Algorithms.Matrix and y as Algorithms.Vector:
    Note: Solve normal equation: (X^T X)^-1 X^T y
    Let X_transpose be transpose_matrix with matrix as X
    Let XtX be matrix_multiply with a as X_transpose and b as X
    Let XtX_inv be matrix_inverse with matrix as XtX
    Let Xty be matrix_vector_multiply with matrix as X_transpose and vector as y
    Let coefficients be matrix_vector_multiply with matrix as XtX_inv and vector as Xty
    
    If model.fit_intercept:
        Set model.intercept to coefficients.data[0]
        Set model.coefficients to slice_vector with vector as coefficients and start as 1 and end as coefficients.size
    Otherwise:
        Set model.intercept to 0.0
        Set model.coefficients to coefficients

Note: Ridge Regression (L2 regularization)
Process called "fit_ridge" that takes model as LinearRegression and X as Algorithms.Matrix and y as Algorithms.Vector:
    Note: Solve: (X^T X + alpha * I)^-1 X^T y
    Let X_transpose be transpose_matrix with matrix as X
    Let XtX be matrix_multiply with a as X_transpose and b as X
    Let I be identity_matrix with size as XtX.rows
    Let regularized_XtX be matrix_add with a as XtX and b as scalar_multiply with scalar as model.alpha and matrix as I
    Let regularized_XtX_inv be matrix_inverse with matrix as regularized_XtX
    Let Xty be matrix_vector_multiply with matrix as X_transpose and vector as y
    Let coefficients be matrix_vector_multiply with matrix as regularized_XtX_inv and vector as Xty
    
    If model.fit_intercept:
        Set model.intercept to coefficients.data[0]
        Set model.coefficients to slice_vector with vector as coefficients and start as 1 and end as coefficients.size
    Otherwise:
        Set model.intercept to 0.0
        Set model.coefficients to coefficients

Note: Lasso Regression (L1 regularization) using coordinate descent
Process called "fit_lasso" that takes model as LinearRegression and X as Algorithms.Matrix and y as Algorithms.Vector:
    Let n_samples be X.rows
    Let n_features be X.cols
    Let max_iter be 1000
    Let tolerance be 0.0001
    
    Note: Initialize coefficients
    Let coefficients be create_zero_vector with size as n_features
    Let intercept be 0.0
    
    Note: Coordinate descent algorithm
    For iteration from 0 to max_iter - 1:
        Let old_coefficients be copy_vector with vector as coefficients
        
        Note: Update intercept if needed
        If model.fit_intercept:
            Let residuals be compute_residuals with X as X and y as y and coefficients as coefficients and intercept as intercept
            Set intercept to compute_mean with vector as residuals
        
        Note: Update each coefficient
        For j from 0 to n_features - 1:
            Let X_j be extract_column with matrix as X and column as j
            Let residuals be compute_partial_residuals with X as X and y as y and coefficients as coefficients and intercept as intercept and exclude_feature as j
            Let rho_j be vector_dot_product with a as X_j and b as residuals
            
            Note: Soft thresholding
            Let X_j_norm_sq be vector_dot_product with a as X_j and b as X_j
            Set coefficients.data[j] to soft_threshold with x as rho_j and threshold as model.alpha and normalization as X_j_norm_sq
        
        Note: Check convergence
        If has_converged with old_coef as old_coefficients and new_coef as coefficients and tolerance as tolerance:
            Break
    
    Set model.coefficients to coefficients
    Set model.intercept to intercept

Note: Prediction methods
Process called "predict_linear_regression" that takes model as LinearRegression and X as Algorithms.Matrix returns Algorithms.Vector:
    Let predictions be list
    
    For i from 0 to X.rows - 1:
        Let prediction be model.intercept
        For j from 0 to model.n_features - 1:
            Set prediction to prediction + model.coefficients.data[j] multiplied by X.data[i][j]
        Add prediction to predictions
    
    Return Algorithms.Vector with:
        size as X.rows
        data as predictions

Note: Polynomial regression
Type called "PolynomialRegression":
    degree as Integer
    linear_model as LinearRegression
    feature_powers as List[List[Integer]]

Process called "create_polynomial_regression" that takes degree as Integer returns PolynomialRegression:
    Return PolynomialRegression with:
        degree as degree
        linear_model as create_linear_regression with fit_intercept as true
        feature_powers as list

Process called "fit_polynomial_regression" that takes model as PolynomialRegression and X as Algorithms.Matrix and y as Algorithms.Vector returns PolynomialRegression:
    Note: Generate polynomial features
    Let poly_features be generate_polynomial_features with X as X and degree as model.degree
    Set model.feature_powers to get_feature_powers with n_features as X.cols and degree as model.degree
    
    Note: Fit linear model on polynomial features
    fit_linear_regression with model as model.linear_model and X as poly_features and y as y
    
    Return model

Process called "predict_polynomial_regression" that takes model as PolynomialRegression and X as Algorithms.Matrix returns Algorithms.Vector:
    Let poly_features be generate_polynomial_features with X as X and degree as model.degree
    Return predict_linear_regression with model as model.linear_model and X as poly_features

Note: Gradient descent implementation
Process called "fit_gradient_descent" that takes model as LinearRegression and X as Algorithms.Matrix and y as Algorithms.Vector and learning_rate as Float and max_iter as Integer:
    Let n_samples be Float.from with value as X.rows
    Let n_features be X.cols
    
    Note: Initialize parameters
    Set model.coefficients to create_zero_vector with size as n_features
    Set model.intercept to 0.0
    
    For iteration from 0 to max_iter - 1:
        Note: Compute predictions
        Let predictions be predict_linear_regression with model as model and X as X
        
        Note: Compute errors
        Let errors be vector_subtract with a as predictions and b as y
        
        Note: Compute gradients
        Let coef_gradients be compute_coefficient_gradients with X as X and errors as errors and n_samples as n_samples
        Let intercept_gradient be compute_intercept_gradient with errors as errors and n_samples as n_samples
        
        Note: Update parameters
        update_coefficients with model as model and gradients as coef_gradients and learning_rate as learning_rate
        update_intercept with model as model and gradient as intercept_gradient and learning_rate as learning_rate

Note: Model evaluation
Process called "score_regression" that takes y_true as Algorithms.Vector and y_pred as Algorithms.Vector returns Float:
    Note: R-squared score
    Let ss_tot be compute_total_sum_of_squares with y as y_true
    Let ss_res be compute_residual_sum_of_squares with y_true as y_true and y_pred as y_pred
    Return 1.0 - ss_res divided by ss_tot

Process called "mean_squared_error" that takes y_true as Algorithms.Vector and y_pred as Algorithms.Vector returns Float:
    Let n be Float.from with value as y_true.size
    Let sum_squared_error be 0.0
    
    For i from 0 to y_true.size - 1:
        Let error be y_true.data[i] - y_pred.data[i]
        Set sum_squared_error to sum_squared_error + error multiplied by error
    
    Return sum_squared_error divided by n

Process called "mean_absolute_error" that takes y_true as Algorithms.Vector and y_pred as Algorithms.Vector returns Float:
    Let n be Float.from with value as y_true.size
    Let sum_absolute_error be 0.0
    
    For i from 0 to y_true.size - 1:
        Let error be Math.abs with x as y_true.data[i] - y_pred.data[i]
        Set sum_absolute_error to sum_absolute_error + error
    
    Return sum_absolute_error divided by n

Note: Utility functions
Process called "add_intercept_column" that takes matrix as Algorithms.Matrix returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Note: Add column of ones for intercept term
    Let new_data be list
    For i from 0 to matrix.rows - 1:
        Let new_row be list containing 1.0
        For j from 0 to matrix.cols - 1:
            Add matrix.data[i][j] to new_row
        Add new_row to new_data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as matrix.rows
        cols as matrix.cols + 1
        data as new_data

Process called "generate_polynomial_features" that takes X as Algorithms.Matrix and degree as Integer returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Note: Generate polynomial features up to specified degree
    Let poly_features be list
    
    For i from 0 to X.rows - 1:
        Let poly_row be list
        Note: Add constant term
        Add 1.0 to poly_row
        
        Note: Add linear terms
        For j from 0 to X.cols - 1:
            Add X.data[i][j] to poly_row
        
        Note: Add higher degree terms
        For d from 2 to degree:
            generate_degree_features with row as X.data[i] and current_degree as d and poly_row as poly_row
        
        Add poly_row to poly_features
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as X.rows
        cols as Collections.List.length with lst as poly_features[0]
        data as poly_features

Process called "soft_threshold" that takes x as Float and threshold as Float and normalization as Float returns Float:
    If x is greater than threshold:
        Return (x - threshold) divided by normalization
    Otherwise if x is less than negative threshold:
        Return (x + threshold) divided by normalization
    Otherwise:
        Return 0.0

Process called "compute_residuals" that takes X as Algorithms.Matrix and y as Algorithms.Vector and coefficients as Algorithms.Vector and intercept as Float returns Algorithms.Vector:
    Let residuals be list
    For i from 0 to X.rows - 1:
        Let prediction be intercept
        For j from 0 to X.cols - 1:
            Set prediction to prediction + coefficients.data[j] multiplied by X.data[i][j]
        Add y.data[i] - prediction to residuals
    
    Return Algorithms.Vector with:
        size as X.rows
        data as residuals

Process called "transpose_matrix" that takes matrix as Algorithms.Matrix returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Note: Would transpose matrix
    Return matrix

Process called "matrix_multiply" that takes a as Algorithms.Matrix and b as Algorithms.Matrix returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Note: Would multiply matrices
    Return a

Process called "matrix_inverse" that takes matrix as Algorithms.Matrix returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Note: Would compute matrix inverse
    Return matrix

Process called "matrix_vector_multiply" that takes matrix as Algorithms.Matrix and vector as Algorithms.Vector returns Algorithms.Vector:
    Note: Would multiply matrix by vector
    Return vector

Process called "create_zero_vector" that takes size as Integer returns Algorithms.Vector:
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to size - 1:
        Add 0.0 to data
    Return Algorithms.Vector with:
        size as size
        data as data

Process called "identity_matrix" that takes size as Integer returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Note: Would create identity matrix
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to size - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to size - 1:
            If i is equal to j:
                Add 1.0 to row
            Otherwise:
                Add 0.0 to row
        Add row to data
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as size
        cols as size
        data as data

Process called "scalar_multiply" that takes scalar as Float and matrix as Algorithms.Matrix returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Note: Would multiply matrix by scalar
    Return matrix

Process called "matrix_add" that takes a as Algorithms.Matrix and b as Algorithms.Matrix returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Note: Would add matrices
    Return a

Process called "vector_subtract" that takes a as Algorithms.Vector and b as Algorithms.Vector returns Algorithms.Vector:
    Note: Would subtract vectors
    Return a

Process called "vector_dot_product" that takes a as Algorithms.Vector and b as Algorithms.Vector returns Float:
    Note: Would compute dot product
    Return 0.0

Process called "copy_vector" that takes vector as Algorithms.Vector returns Algorithms.Vector:
    Note: Would copy vector
    Return vector

Process called "has_converged" that takes old_coef as Algorithms.Vector and new_coef as Algorithms.Vector and tolerance as Float returns Boolean:
    Note: Would check convergence
    Return false

Process called "slice_vector" that takes vector as Algorithms.Vector and start as Integer and end as Integer returns Algorithms.Vector:
    Note: Would slice vector
    Return vector

Process called "extract_column" that takes matrix as Algorithms.Matrix and column as Integer returns Algorithms.Vector:
    Note: Would extract column as vector
    Return Algorithms.Vector with size as 0 and data as list

Process called "compute_partial_residuals" that takes X as Algorithms.Matrix and y as Algorithms.Vector and coefficients as Algorithms.Vector and intercept as Float and exclude_feature as Integer returns Algorithms.Vector:
    Note: Would compute residuals excluding one feature
    Return y

Process called "compute_mean" that takes vector as Algorithms.Vector returns Float:
    Note: Would compute mean
    Return 0.0

Process called "normalize_features" that takes matrix as Algorithms.Matrix returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Note: Would normalize features
    Return matrix

Process called "get_feature_powers" that takes n_features as Integer and degree as Integer returns List[List[Integer]]:
    Note: Would generate feature power combinations
    Return list

Process called "generate_degree_features" that takes row as List[Float] and current_degree as Integer and poly_row as List[Float]:
    Note: Would generate features for specific degree
    Return

Process called "compute_coefficient_gradients" that takes X as Algorithms.Matrix and errors as Algorithms.Vector and n_samples as Float returns Algorithms.Vector:
    Note: Would compute gradients for coefficients
    Return Algorithms.Vector with size as 0 and data as list

Process called "compute_intercept_gradient" that takes errors as Algorithms.Vector and n_samples as Float returns Float:
    Note: Would compute gradient for intercept
    Return 0.0

Process called "update_coefficients" that takes model as LinearRegression and gradients as Algorithms.Vector and learning_rate as Float:
    Note: Would update coefficients
    Return

Process called "update_intercept" that takes model as LinearRegression and gradient as Float and learning_rate as Float:
    Note: Would update intercept
    Return

Process called "compute_total_sum_of_squares" that takes y as Algorithms.Vector returns Float:
    Note: Would compute total sum of squares
    Return 0.0

Process called "compute_residual_sum_of_squares" that takes y_true as Algorithms.Vector and y_pred as Algorithms.Vector returns Float:
    Note: Would compute residual sum of squares
    Return 0.0